    <h2 id="what-is-an-entity">What is an entity?</h2>

    <p>An entity is a recognisable thing: a company, person, product, place, concept, or organisation.</p>

    <p>In SEO and AI search, the useful question is not “does Google see this keyword?” It is “does the system understand this brand as a distinct thing with clear relationships?”</p>

    <p>If your brand is consistently associated with a category, problem, or expertise area, it becomes easier for AI systems to mention or recommend you. If the signals are vague, you become harder to trust and harder to retrieve as a relevant answer.</p>

    <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why entity SEO matters for AI search</h2>

    <p>AI search systems need confidence. They prefer brands that are easier to explain and verify.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Rankings</strong> show that a page is visible.</li>
      <li><strong>Citations</strong> show that a page was selected as a source.</li>
      <li><strong>Entity signals</strong> help the system understand the brand behind the source.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This is why two pages with similar quality can perform differently in AI search. One belongs to a brand with stronger recognition, clearer positioning, and more external evidence. The other looks isolated.</p>

    <p>If you want the broader context, read <a href="/why-some-brands-get-mentioned-by-ai-and-others-dont/">Why Some Brands Get Mentioned by AI and Others Don’t</a>.</p>

    <h2 id="signals">The signals behind entity SEO</h2>

    <table class="table-ctm">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Signal</th>
          <th>What it tells AI</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Consistent naming</td>
          <td>This brand is clearly the same thing across the web</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>About and service clarity</td>
          <td>This is what the brand does and who it helps</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Schema markup</td>
          <td>People, organisations and services are easier to interpret</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Third-party mentions</td>
          <td>Other sources recognise this brand</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Topical content clusters</td>
          <td>This brand keeps showing up around the same topic</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2 id="improve">How to improve your entity footprint</h2>

    <h3>1. Make your positioning easier to repeat</h3>
    <p>Your homepage, About page, service pages, social profiles, and directory listings should not tell five different stories.</p>

    <h3>2. Strengthen your topic associations</h3>
    <p>Build clusters around the subjects you want to be known for. If AI search is one of them, connect your pages on AEO, citations, mentions, AI Overviews, Perplexity, GA4 and strategy.</p>

    <h3>3. Use schema where it removes ambiguity</h3>
    <p>Organization, Person, Article, FAQPage and Service schema do not create authority by themselves, but they help machines interpret what is already there.</p>

    <h3>4. Earn mentions, not just links</h3>
    <p>If relevant sites mention your brand, include you in roundups, quote you, or cite your work, the external evidence around your entity gets stronger.</p>

    <h3>5. Keep author and proof signals visible</h3>
    <p>Real authors, clear bios, examples, proof and current updates make entity signals more believable.</p>

    <h2 id="mistakes">Common entity SEO mistakes</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Inconsistent brand naming across website and external profiles.</li>
      <li>Generic service pages with weak category language.</li>
      <li>No About page that explains what the brand is known for.</li>
      <li>Publishing content across too many unrelated topics.</li>
      <li>Treating schema as a substitute for clarity.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What good looks like</h2>

    <p>A strong entity footprint makes it easier for AI systems to answer questions like:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Who is this brand?</li>
      <li>What topic does it belong to?</li>
      <li>Why would it be worth mentioning?</li>
      <li>What evidence supports that?</li>
    </ul>

    <p>If those answers are obvious, you become easier to cite and easier to recommend.</p>

    <h2 id="faq">FAQ: Entity SEO</h2>

    <h3>What is entity SEO in simple terms?</h3>
    <p>It is the work of making your brand easier for search engines and AI systems to understand as a distinct, trustworthy thing.</p>

    <h3>Does entity SEO replace keyword SEO?</h3>
    <p>No. It adds another layer. Keywords still help with retrieval. Entity signals help with trust and recognition.</p>

    <h3>Why does entity SEO matter more in AI search?</h3>
    <p>Because AI systems do not only retrieve pages. They also infer which brands are credible enough to mention or recommend.</p>

    <h3>What should I improve first?</h3>
    <p>Usually: clearer positioning, better About/service pages, stronger topical clusters, cleaner schema and more consistent external references.</p>

